 Let's use the binomial probability formula \[
P(X = k) = \binom{n}{k} p^k (1-p)^{n-k}
\] where $n$ is the number of trials, $k$ is the number of successes, $p$ is the probability of success on each trial. We also need to multiply by the number of possible outcomes for the $k$ successes. On a normal 7-day week, the probability that any particular person's birthday is on Tuesday is $\dfrac{1}{7}$, and the probability they are not born on Tuesday is $\dfrac{6}{7}$. Thus, applying the binomial probability formula, we see that the probability that $k$ people's birthdays are on Tuesday is \[
\binom{3}{k} \Big(\dfrac{1}{7}\Big)^k \Big(\dfrac{6}{7}\Big)^{3-k}
\] Once we have $k$ people's birthdays on Tuesday because $\dfrac{1}{7}$ was the probability of any single person's birthday being on Tuesday, we have $k$ people out of 3 who have their birthdays on Tuesday. Therefore, the number of ways to choose those $k$ people is $\binom{3}{k}$. Simplifying, the probability that exactly 2 of Amy's 3 closest friends have their birthday on Tuesday is \[
\binom{3}{2} \Big(\dfrac{1}{7}\Big)^2 \Big(\dfrac{6}{7}\Big)^{3-2}
\] <answer> $\boxed{\dfrac{18}{343}}$ </answer>

